Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, in an amendment to the criminal law, the proposed cancellation of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs have denied in the second reading of the draft amendment to reduce penalties for economic crimes, which could open the doors of freedom for the former First Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having reached an agreement in principle disadvantageous with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not final, and the court must rule on the appeal of the convicted in December.
Tymosenko describes the judgment of revenge in the political system and caused a process of suspicion of bias of the court, also in the west.
The project to cancel the paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Premère Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have required 226 votes to approve it.
