The finest swimming pools of Europe
A leap in the blue
Julia Stanek
Pataugeoires in perspective ovni, wonderful swimming pools in Budapest: travelling across Europe can live his blue miracle - and turned the city or a long walk, can leave its tired legs in carbonated water baths.
A book shows how pool swimming can be the most experience of well-being.
When Iris Meder would travel research during the past 18 months, there is an object that should not be missed in his luggage: a bathing suit.
Lying on his back in the water, she retorted cupolas artistically arranged and swam against Putten marbles that was waiting on the other side of the pool and was to admire the Art Nouveau meticulously restored these converted swimming pools.
If a covered swimming pool it was fun, she noted in his book without delay all the details of interest on the type of construction and the history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools were surveyed in this way by the architecture historian Meder and presented them in his book published: "Badefreuden (Bain Joies." The municipal swimming pools covered in Munich, the historic bath palaces in the Black Forest, "concrete buildings Hardcore" in the Taunus.
It has led his travel to the most exceptional baths of Central Europe " in 13 countries; Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited respectively places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland and Luxembourg city, Serbia and Croatia.
The German 46 years is a fervent true culture bath.
Meder, explains that it is not a lot of interest in sport but restrictive feels attracted to water in a completely different way.
It is irritating that fans swimming should simply look blue tiles and accommodate the stench of bleach while joggers breathe the spellbinding fragrance of spruce forests or can listen to the birds trill Merry Park.
"I asked myself one day why pools must always be so ugly," said the Viennese.
"I started so a collection of beautiful baths."
The surface of the water reinforces architecture
A dive into a swimming pool and sauna volatile oils - factor welfare in swimming are enormous because all are awake, according to Meder.
And if the builders would have given a little more punishment rooms to swim could be a real treat for the eyes: "instead of a floor was a surface water in the halls of swimming."
"It is a transparent side, but reflects on the other hand, however, the beauty of the entire building."
All surfaces are optically double: high arches, multicoloured tiles, springboards.
The volume of small format "image" Badefreuden reported worthy of 190 pages on the history of architecture and culture on the oasis of historic welfare - he certainly want to make a leap into the blue.
The collector Meder discovered remarkable copies during its research in Hungary.
Alongside the baths splendid welfare as the Széchenyi bath aged 100 years in Budapest, she found water containing nitrate in a natural cave in the bath karst cave in Miskolc-Tapolca) and a bath baths whose basins are filled with water containing alkali and (Városi Termálfürdö in Jászberény) and located in a building-shaped bottle.
By contrast, pools heated outdoor Switzerland and Austria offers spectacular views, while a roof bath in Zurich was the entire city in his eyes, you can admire the snowy Arlberg from an external pool of St. Anton: the Turkish bath is equipped with a window from which we can observe animation on the ski trail.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design expects swimmers in Längenfeld: Ötztal Aqua Dome resembles unidentified flying objects that has just landed on the Alps.
In winter, steam rises three open shelves, while in the background are the mountains of the Ötztal towards the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
The smell of bleach does not come from all pools of Meder collection.
Many thermal baths from a smell of sulphur, Árpád-spa in the Hungarian Bekescsaba emanates a strong smell of oil, it is hard to believe, to find themselves in a health spa.
The smell comes from therapeutic alkaline waters containing hydrogen, which is almost black and silt you glue skin as soon as you let slide into the pool - a spa experience.
During his pursuit of beautiful swimming pools, Iris Meder also suffered disappointments: when she wanted to visit Bad Luhatschowitz, a free outdoor swimming pool and outdoor of Czechoslovakia, she was found in a field barrricaded.
The bath designed by the architèque Dušan Jurkovic in 1902 was meanwhile closed.
A glance through the window of the building-Art Nouveau in red-white-yellow, she observed the flourishing weeds between tiles.
She has observed an opposite effect in a charming swimming pool in the Black Forest: the palace of spas of Bad Wildbad.
This building has already survived three phases; you can discover not only elements of neo-Roman leaving since its conception in 1844, but still a Moorish room Alhambra style which was added in 1900.
Since its careful modernization of 1995, the thermal palace remains the favorite bath expert pool, Iris Meder - and not just because she is a native of Schwarzwald.
"It is already a beautiful performance of melting styles so different construction unit so great," said Meder.
With such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a minor issue.
Agricultural speculation
The German bank examines in detail the speculation on the raw materials
Christian Teevs
The German bank abandons its speculation on the raw materials?
According to SPIEGEL ONLINE, Josef Ackermann has established a working group to explore the consequences of speculation for the world's poor.
In January, the leader of the group then wants to draw the consequences.
Hamburg -
For the citizens of the Federal Republic, the thing is clear: according to a study, 84% of Germans find unacceptable that the banks are speculating on raw materials such as corn and wheat.
Two-thirds of respondents even require the German bank and other credit institutions discontinuent this Avenue business because it increases the problems of the poorest in the world.
It is the result of a Forsa survey on the order of the consumer organization Foodwatch.
The study is based on a report presented by Foodwatch in mid-October.
The author Harald Schumann emphasizes in this article that speculation Awards on global commodities, pushing prices upwards and that banks share complicity in global hunger.
The campaign to protect consumers aligns specifically against the head of Deutsche Bank, Josef Ackermann, even if the big banks like Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley are acting in the same way.
Speculation on raw materials was originally introduced to protect merchants against price fluctuations.
But the majority of experts share meanwhile opinion that bettors have posted offers and demand - and benefit at the expense of the very poor.
Ackermann responded to criticism differently from American competitors: he promised to investigate the accusations and said, "no case is worth the good reputation of Deutsche Bank."
According to information SPIEGEL ONLINE an international working group is currently examining accusations of Foodwatch-Report.
The review should be completed by the end of the year, then the results of the board of Deutsche Bank must be presented - with recommendation of habit.
In late January, the head of the Bank will indicate the consequences.
This could result in a reduction in the market for raw materials, or even a complete abandonment.
Ackermann built its image
The head of Foodwatch Thilo Bode welcomed the news, but at the same time confirmed its criticism of the financial sector: "speculation on rising food prices shows a particularly drastic, how banks today are detrimental to the public interest."
Ackermann is the first banking lobby to be particularly today under obligation.
"Deutsche Bank must remove all investments in its portfolio, for which money has been invested on food speculation," said Bode.
"It matters little to Mr Ackermann, if it is a question of hungry people, or if the reputation of the Deutsche Bank is at stake."
The awareness of Ackermann may at first seem surprising, but it is clear that the CEO of the group wants to introduce a perfect image, a few months before he left office.
Deutsche Bank did announce on Monday that the chairman of the Board of Directors will not change what is planned within the Board of Governors.
It could improve its image with an abandonment of controversial agricultural speculation.
And about potential losses, it has little to worry about - his successor will care.
One in two would terminate investments on raw materials.
Foodwatch strives to maintain a strong pressure on the Manager.
To date more than 30000 Internet users have already participated in the campaign of the organization.
Bode published the survey Tuesday, with the November 7 and 8, the Forsa Institute conducted questionnaires with 1001 people.
Just 11 percent found it legitimate that Deutsche Bank proposes investments for which bets on the price of food products are made.
Many customers of the bank would also personal consequences if they learned that their bank is involved in such operations: one in two would terminate following the poll, all investments for which money is injected into speculation on raw materials.
43 percent déconseilleraient such a bank to their entourage, 49% said they would seek to terminate their account to change " banking institution.
21 home in Vienna
The Pavilion has moved
To Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with high, low and Happy End: the Austrian flag for exhibitions in Brussels in 1958, has won awards, has been a museum in Vienna, remained empty, then fell into ruins.
Now it is open and takes the place of home exposure.
If there is enthusiasm for a modern postwar architecture, for his clear forms, its glass sheds, its strong and bold proportions and its new construction materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the flag of the Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958, is a good and famous example.
The Pavilion Schwanzer once received the "Grand Prix" architecture for its construction steel and glass, light and suspended.
The construction is seen until today as an important step in the contemporary architecture.
He has made so famous architects, he has also built the Pavilion for the Austrian universal exhibition.
With its legendary house, four-cylinder BMW and its adjacent construction-shaped bowl in Munich, he finally became famous internationally in 1973.
Its draft flag as a temporary construction had been exposed after the universal exhibition in Switzerland Garden at the station south of Vienna, has been transformed, and in 1962 as a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, not a good environment.
However, it was also long used until contemporary art gets a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building was empty and increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it is now known as the "home of the 21 century" and in the future will be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere museum opened, the house, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck at any point of view.
The new departure was carried out by Agnes Husslein-Arco, which has become the new director in 2007 of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, promoted a historian of art to another between considerable career in his youth of skater, with Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and the founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she led particularly the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments, it has received public funds and private sponsorship and exploitation.
Except for contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba which bears the same name were exposed, a coffee and a bookshop, and an office must be built.
Strict surveillance, small budget
For the Krischanitz achievement was the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had changed and expanded sensitively secession of Joseph Olbracht and that he had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that the flag was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "virtually every weekend" exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness following his trip to Vienna and change of use.
During the current changes, there were big problems: the building was "an abyss of energy," said Krischanitz.
The profiles of window glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced glass fibre was raised and the roof replaced by a safety glass.
The joists of thermal bridges have been strengthened or replaced, and coatings filled with asbestos have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a sign of light sifted between home and road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the front - it is almost a new construction, but always the slight Pavilion Schwanzer.
The exterior doors origins remained, the house is painted in a shade protection against rust red-brown colour.
And the cinema is identical to what it once was.
And all this under close supervision of authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that are good and cheap to be found, and which also delight in the office of protecting monuments," said Krischanitz and it draws attention to a gross floor basement.
Despite all the constraints, the problems and the transformations, building remained flexible and lightweight.
This would have been difficult with the Pavilion, " which came from Brussels, " said Krischanitz recently, a typical story of ' Drop-in-the-City. "
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and despite everything "awaken the good conscience."
But in this case the House of the 21 century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of luck for urban construction: around the Garden Switzerland is precisely the "neighborhood of Central Station" any newly planned, with offices and apartments.
And another stroke of luck perhaps will happen: the House of the 21 century could benefit from the addition of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the centre of Berlin temporary art, and as he said, it is already negotiating with the city to get a site in the vicinity of the Garden Switzerland.
