The railway corporation has developed a plan crisis, which aims to prevent accidents in winter.
The number of employees is expected to double.
It costs millions.
In the battle against the train accidents related to the winter season and delays, the company railway Deutsche Bahn " will spend more than 70 million this year.
" The daily Bild-Zeitung reported beforehand, citing an internal crisis in the group that investments by a total of approximately EUR 300 million would be provided until 2015.
This should enable better availability of vehicles and the rail network, also in the case of extreme weather.
The number of internal and external employees for snow removal of rail facilities and docks should, among other double and switch to 16000 people.
The goal is to rid the wharves of snow and ice until the beginning of the phase of service and 90 percent of track equipment needed to service in a period of four to five hours.
Two months ago the head of station Rüdiger Grube has warned the government and industry at a conference at the summit of train accidents this winter.
Last winter the railway corporation has had a lot of problems for the transport of users, because it lacks among other reserves in case of difficult weather conditions.
That is how many new regional trains have been waiting for years an authorization from the Ministry of Railways.
In addition, there is a delay in the delivery of ICE trains.
The railway company has for years of what to do, given that it has to verify the axles ICE trains far more often in the workshop, after a break of axles took place on an ICE in the central station in Cologne.
The German bank Deutsche Bank " pays millions of penalties in the US.
After the chief Josef Ackermann there is something new in the US: the German bank Deutsche Bank "must pay a fine" to the tune of millions.
As if the problems of Deutsche Bank were not already enough, the past of this giant of the industry is catching up in the US: the Institute of Frankfurt pays compared to $145 million (EUR 106 million) to settle a dispute because of the collapse of five major cooperative banks during the financial crisis.
It is the sale of mortgage documents.
The regulator of financial markets NCUA door to big banks a series of accusations, and for encouraging cooperative banks to make false promises regarding the purchase of financial products; they would have minimized the risks.
These documents have lost considerable value during the financial crisis and have led banks downwards.
"We are pleased to have been able to find a solution to this issue, without the parties begin proceedings in court," said a partner of Deutsche Bank in New York.
The Bank has recognised in comparison no fault.
It is also valid for Citigroup, which is committed to a payment of $20.5 million.
The NCUA Chairman Debbie Matz welcomed the concessions from both banks.
The National Credit Union Administration (NCUA) responsible for cooperative banks in the US and it intervenes in the event of bankruptcy, in order to protect customer deposits.
The NCUA is trying to repair the damage incurred billions of dollars.
Comparisons concluded now are the first in their kind.
The regulator has also taken other large banks and in the summer he was assigned to Court JP Morgan Chase, the Royal Bank of Scotland and Goldman Sachs.
Regarding the issue of mortgage documents "mortgage-backed securities."
The credit houses are at the base.
When the US housing bubble burst in 2007, This was fatal for a large number of banking companies.
In September 2008, at the top of the financial crisis, the investment bank US Lehman Brothers collapsed.
Even though the events are already a few years ago, at the moment it is blowing on American banks a wind storm.
Investors and the supervisory authorities have filed numerous appeals to obtain compensation or to punish misconduct.
The Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA) triggered the biggest wave of complaints.
It accuses 18 large international banks, two financial house of American state Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac's benefit in kind when business mortgage of about $200 billion.
Deutsche Bank must also file an appeal with the FHFA, it is several operations for a total of $14.2 billion for the years 2005 to 2007.
The supervisory authorities are asking that the Frankfurter responds "substantial losses" but without mentioning a specific sum.
Deutsche Bank had rejected the applications as unjustified and says they want to defend themselves.
