The bank scandal Lake Zurich
The most adventurous Bank of Europe is not in France or Italy, but in Switzerland.
UBS went bankrupt almost in the financial crisis and patina meanwhile from one crisis to another.
It is a German who must now lead.
It is certainly not what Axel Weber had imagined.
After his dramatic departure from the head of the Bundesbank; it was informed in July that it would be in 2013.00 a.m.st as spectacular: President of the Board of Directors of the great Swiss bank UBS - a major step towards an unexpected and lucrative career.
Axel Weber has publicly welcomed welcomed; Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its strength recently obtained and made kind comments on the future colleagues.
"UBS has passed the Turnaround."
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel."
And yet, in September it was clear that everything was going to change.
A merchant securities UBS in London had diverted all security systems of the Bank and had soared about 1.7 billion euros.
The head of the board of directors of UBS Oswald Grübel, a well-known banker, not only in Switzerland, had to leave.
The President of the board of directors of UBS is regarded as since suffering - and asking: when Axel Weber is it finally?
We have already learned that Weber may be advised the bank from February 2012.
And it will resume the presidency administration already in May - not in 2013, as the bank had disclosed Tuesday.
For Axel Weber that becomes difficult.
It is not a banker, much more professor of economics and President of the bank, and it would certainly have needed a period of adjustment.
Suddenly it then assumes responsibility for the strategy of a bank, which has yet to prove once again that it has long since earned the title of "the biggest bank scandal in Europe."
Indeed, UBS is a huge side - until recently, it was the largest asset manager in the world, and on the other hand, it is faltering for years of a scandal.
Nothing, it seems, the savings so proud Swiss bank.
It started during the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the Swiss asset manager, silent and sound, but also crafty, she had combined with ambitious goals: it also wanted to be in the area of investment banking, a very large bank.
Therefore, UBS managed a side in 2007 with $1.6 billion more money from a wealthy clientele than any other bank in the world.
On the other hand, she had advanced as investment bank in the league of the world's largest banks.
This has made an impression.
The former banker Hans Geiger and later a professor of bank for many years in Zurich says: "I have always taken the UBS as a model of good bank in front of my students."
"In the current context, one wonders: how is it that I could simply be wrong at this point?"
It is profoundly wrong.
In 2007, it became clear that for the first time something was amiss at UBS.
In the middle of the year President Peter Wuffli withdrew surprisingly, which had hitherto been perceived as a high intellectual as well as a brilliant banker.
A few months later it was considered for what reasons he was gone.
The division of the bank had soared with sub-prime documents and write off billions.
To support this, UBS announced a capital increase of $13 billion francs and made a cross.
For this she has actually found investors, but shortly before, would froncé eyebrows: a non-transparent Asian state from Singapore and a background of Arab state, which was passed over in silence, to the point that it has never learned his name.
This is, however, that the first blow.
In April 2008 it has worsened.
The bank was to announce new losses amounting to billions, the chairman of the board of directors Marcel Ospel, who was still in 2006, the second-best paid board of Switzerland, withdrew.
In October 2008 the disaster followed: UBS was, given its investment errors in the financial crisis before bankruptcy and had to be rescued by the state.
The national bank has bought UBS tens of billions of securities issues, the Swiss Confederation has given six billion francs for convertible bonds, for which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
Throughout Switzerland has been shaken - because she noted how this can be dramatic for a small country to host such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS's 2007 " rose to more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see chart).
"We have not been able to save UBS again," said the researcher from banks, Geiger.
After the first disaster followed the second.
A few months before, UBS had surrendered because of a tax dispute with America and expressed its willingness to publish the data of the wealthy clientele, who had defrauded the taxman, perhaps with the help of the Bank.
In addition, she accepted a payment of $780 million in repayment of unjustified profits from these operations with a fine plus.
And UBS has more or less published that she had helped to tax fraud.
At the same time it has lost something that has always been its capital in competition with the wealthy clients: the prestige of the discretion.
After the scandal Swiss banking secrecy has not been the same.
It was followed by the withdrawal of the head of the board of directors and the chairman of the board of directors.
And the exodus of money from clients.
And the bank had lost its credibility a few months in the two main areas: investment banking because of bad speculation and asset management because of aid for tax fraud.
And, as there was somewhat of a return to calm and, as had been thought that UBS would manage, he followed this unfortunate history of merchants: a single title merchant wildly EUR 1.7 billion, before the bank realization that something was amiss.
And it publishes: with risk management in the investment bank that does not always seems to work.
"With the Adoboli case, it was found that the risk control too little changed," said Martin Janssen, an economist and professor of finance at the Banking Institute at the University of Zurich.
The financial director of a large German bank is safe: "the problem of UBS is that it has no risk control."
However, it was exactly the idea of caution with which the Swiss bankers had long since taken their function, to become the guardian of the great wealth of the world: not too big risks, but security for money - and the world could collapse beyond the Alpine republic.
The treasures of Swiss banks had become the symbol of an unshakeable reliability as Lindt & Sprüngli for a particularly noble chocolate.
The UBS in Zurich still goes hand in hand with the solid cliché of the Swiss private bank - it is only a little larger.
The situation is classic.
The Bank has its headquarters in the central station of Zurich, which leads directly from the central station in Lake Zurich, which itself is surrounded by snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are prestigious, rents stores are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellers as Tiffany's, is here between the Swiss traditions stores as well as those of the Sprüngli confectionery.
For centuries the Swiss bankers have resided here: the national bank through the palace's Credit Suisse to elitist private banks as Julius Bär.
It arrives in the lobby of the UBS through a heavy door.
Inside, the walls are lined with marble, to lie thick leather chairs, and alongside the logo of the bank, a major label for "safe."
UBS knows what the customer research here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has one day off the market - or betrayed the two major Swiss banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, as the leader of a small private Swiss bank.
He would prefer not to read his name in the newspaper, finally as all Swiss bankers he does business with the two big banks.
UBS would become far too much, there - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons were also widespread.
The Swiss had nothing more to say.
"And even when they have long since been adapted to the mores of the Anglo-Saxons."
This was the investment bank Anglo-Saxon changed UBS, it has made high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost so much money in the jungle of sub-prime as the big Swiss bank.
The disaster became apparent on 15 October 2008.
"This Wednesday, the coalition government of the small country to seven million inhabitants has undertaken the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," wrote the author Lukas Hässig in his book "the crash of UBS."
With up to about 68 billion francs, or 45 billion euros, politicians have agreed to save the large bank of bankruptcy.
How could it happen?
If we are talking with Swiss bankers, they see the problem mainly to the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks have reached a huge group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for the small Swiss - and was constantly increasing.
What helped is that the two different prédécesseuses banks UBS have completed: a rich bank, but lethargy with strong asset management in Zurich and poorer, but certainly already highly internationalized.
Suddenly, the international investment banks have been positively access to a lot of money, with which they have been able to turn a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with the rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, from 2001 to 2007 Head of UBS Group, and Marcel Ospel, formerly chairman of the board of directors.
"I have always thought that Wuffli and Ospel constituted a dream team," said the researcher banks, Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the great intellectual modest, which are very good in models and statistics, and Ospel, intuitive, which has found its way to the summit with the learning of the bank."
But Ospel would relied until the end to Wuffli.
And wuffli would probably have committed at the end of a decisive error: "he thought that his models were the reality," said Geiger.
"It is a tragic fall."
Tragic, perhaps.
One thing is clear: the exuberance arrived before the fall.
The staff of the UBS remembers clearly leaders meetings during which the leader of the group Wuffli gave the same watchword: dethrone Goldman Sachs.
The US bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
It has commissioned the "League Tables" rankings, which have documented the success at the time of the banks.
After all, UBS wanted to climb while high.
Some steps have already been successful.
In case of currencies and transactions in securities it has played a very important role.
Business advisers, who have had responsibility, highlighted a weakness, however: in the international operations of interest in banking jargon "Fixed income," there would be a huge difference compared to the largest banks.
UBS would have gaps in US mortgage products.
To fill this gap, UBS has launched into an adventure, which almost cost the lives.
Hungry for growth, it is also the bank itself that a fund created before it in the US sub-prime investments that have invested.
It has turned into a massive machine that is packaged and documents of value based on US mortgages - but has also retained risks.
Even when other banks sought long down.
"Even in the summer of 2007, while the US housing market was in flames, UBS bought here," said Geiger, the banking expert.
