Crows smart spread in cities
In many places, freux are considered "problem of birds" but experts say that these highly intelligent animals are no longer hunt cities for a long time.
Some love, some want to get rid of them as quickly as possible. Crows belong to the city for centuries, but in many communities, residents ' complaints are increasing because of the dirt and noise of animals.
An antidote to the "problem" is not yet in sight.
In the first ostfriesisch symposium on crows, experts have said that this is no longer possible to drive the freux cities.
Experts from throughout Germany deliberated on possible solutions.
They are looking for alternatives in cities
The protectors of nature makes the problems of cities on the exodus of freux particularly protected: the use of chemicals in agriculture destroy increasingly vital traditional spaces.
Hunting, development and logging brood typical made life difficult for birds.
Crows are under the protection of nature.
There are large settlements with more than 600 breeding pairs in the westfälischen Soest, in north-west including Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen and Leer.
In 2005, a controversial project had earned negative ads because of the massacre of crows in this region.
Critics have found the capture birds in traps and killing with batons particularly brutal.
"Normal expulsion, ousted, serves no purpose," the planner of the city and the landscape of Leer, Werner Klöver.
The destruction of nests with water under pressure or cut down trees, often produced unintended consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"Animals deviate, large colonies are divided and they disperse in other places."
" The ousting is conceivable only in exceptional cases, such as in hospitals, retirement homes or schools.
"We are forced to live with them, we can no longer kill them."
The problem is not solved in cities without the inclusion of the periphery, according to the opinion of the mayor Wolfgang Kellner of Leer.
Conceivable is a combination of the ousting of animals to a aversif packaging and glittering offers to help resettle elsewhere.
Psychologist and ethnologist, Uta Maria Jûrgens prospectait " info panels in place of chainsaws to completely different relations: " we can finally better withstand a button in the face with a dose of confidence. "
Jûrgens has co-founded the Ascheberger-path-education baskets in Schleswig-Holstein, road signs informing on the lives of these highly intelligent freux.
This project has been adopted by tourists.
Jürgen gave his own opinion about the criticism of the noise caused by birds: "this is a large number of communication, these birds have much to say."
The intelligence and the ability of animals are legendary: the freux use not only instruments work to arrive at a feast, but they make their tools themselves as instruments of work.
The éthologistes Cambridge University tested four freux recently, how is the intelligence of the birds.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to do down scaffolding with stones in order to achieve a larva.
Without a lot of training, they déterminément recognized that a stone should have some size and shape to collapse the platform.
In a second trial, crows astute then had to solve a problem more stout.
In a cylinder placed vertically, researchers had placed a small bucket with a larva.
The birds could not reach their booty with their beak.
However, the researchers had put pieces of wire at their disposal.
All four animals formed a hook with which they fished the little bucket of small pipe.
Three of the four freux are even from the start.
