The mass slaughter of staff
The new book by Peter Englund offers depth and generosity. "The Beauty and the Sorrow: an Intimate History of the First World War" (The beauty and sorrow: an intimate history of the First World War), it begins with a long list of characters you greenhouse heart.
A board to begin: carefully tear this page and make your mark-page.
You will learn about these people in detail in this romantic tale of Peter Englund, the list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be disturbed and desperate in the fog of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
It is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which issues the Nobel Prize for literature.
He wrote a book out of the ordinary that it describes, accurately, as "a book of anti-history."
It contains a few familiar names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion on strategies and equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, " he says, " a book outlining how this might look like. " The " sentiments, impressions, experiences and moods. "
"The beauty and sorrow" summarizes the experiences in war 20 men and women more or less ordinary on both sides of the war, young schoolgirls and botanists in there, doctors, ambulance and sellers.
Some will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war; some will lose members, will become crazy or will lose their lives.
Their lives here reeling as candles church: while some lapse, new revival.
The book by Peter Englund departs from the traditional history books.
It provides a corrective to the idea that the First World War is more than the terrible war trenches on the Western Front.
"The beauty and sorrow" ably described other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the eastern front, Mesopotamia and eastern Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; a Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people as a natural disaster like a hurricane Katrina that reeks of the cordite still hanging.
When gun ringing in the distance, and you are a mother at home, stay or walk away from you?
That will come anyway?
Almost nobody can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, the lack of facts has been augmented by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours. "
"The beauty and sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse within the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor on the high seas fleet German.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying and exciting, but are more preserved through the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most tackle deprivation and the ability to cope.
By telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "ersatz, ersatz everywhere."
"Coffee replacement, forged aluminum, imitation of rubber, paper, wood buttons."
He goes on food replacement in Germany.
He describes the meat of rice cooked in fat sheep (and finished with a fake wood bones); tobacco manufactured with dry roots and skin dried potato; shoe soles wood. "
He says that "837 meat substitutes allowed are registered in the production of sausages, also 511 alternative cafes."
Some stories address the honour and courage.
An American acknowledges its own drive to the savagery and says about the war: " you feel that, after all, that is what men, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and instead of pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there was no barbaric behind your formal shirt and cloutée.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that it is likely to die, and that nobody will notice or pay attention.
"When one is resigned to sacrifice themselves, we hope to have an audience," he wrote.
Unfortunately, it is rather similar to "a condemned man strangled in secret."
Other comments relate to the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
"The conflict is becoming increasingly a history of economic competition," writes Peter Englund, "a war between the plants."
It captures the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the bestiaire the beginning of the century: the mass murderer well articulated and ideologically confident, well-cut clothes, which executes its butchery while seated behind a desk."
People act in unexpected ways; there are so many basic behaviors that heroism.
Peter Englund spoke of soldiers who have tried at all costs to catch a venereal disease among prostitutes in order to avoid the service at the front.
"We find the most grotesque expression in the trade of pus due to gonorrhea, that soldiers buy and splashed on the genitals in the hope of ending up in hospital," he writes.
"The most desperate to apply on the eyes, which translates into a lifetime blindness."
In this translation from the Swedish by Peter Graves, the prose of Peter Englund is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly suited to its task of humanity.
In dozens of short scenes, it captures how the war has "triggered exclusively uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, a social revolution, an aversion to religion."
People are beginning to wonder why their leaders do their war.
The best books on the First World War are often indirect, such as ' Great War and Modern Memory " (The Great War and Modern Memory) Paul Fussel, or " west nothing new, " Erich Maria Note, rather than complete.
The book by Peter Englund is somewhat conventional pantheon.
The end of the book is the most damning that I read in a non-fictionnelle.
I do not reveal.
But it is as if he had emerged from his book, your hands this page containing the list of people and burned with a match.
