The union of school aid continues the city for redundancies
The union that represents hundreds of school aid who lost their jobs last month plans to initiate a trial Wednesday in the city for unnecessary and discriminatory redundancies. The impact is disproportionate schools serving disadvantaged schoolchildren.
The prosecution is probably the ultimate weapon of the union, the Council's 37th District, to try to reverse the dismissals.
Six hundred and seventy-two school aid coordinators of parents and other employees, part of the lowest paid in the city, have lost their jobs on 7 October; the union leaders have compared these redundancies to a political revenge for not having left the city access to a fund for health care, led by groups of workers, and that would have enabled us to close the gap in the budget last spring.
Municipal authorities have strongly denied the accusation.
At a hearing of the City Council last month, Chancellor Dennis M. Walcott said that the redundancies were part of the budget closed in June.
A Council member retaliated, stating that the dismissals of school aid were not specified in the budget.
Officers of the Council's 37th District said they fulfilled a notice of claim, warning the Department of Education that he would be prosecuted; a press conference will be held Wednesday to formally announce the prosecution at the State Supreme Court in Manhattan.
Dennis M. Walcott and the Department of Education of the City will be the defendant. Grievors will be represented by eight workers laid off, all black or Latino origin, like most school aid that have lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, spokesman for the legal department of the city, said that the municipality has not yet been able to see the reasons for the trial and therefore cannot comment on the allegations.
According to a draft obtained by the New York Times, the union capitalizes on the number of redundancies in schools in the poorest neighbourhoods of the city to support his complaint against unfair treatment, saying that the poorest schools would lose the most aid because of a regular under-funding.
While there are no redundancies on Staten Island, and some in the institutions of Upper East Side or TriBeCa, 17 school aid have lost their jobs in the 23 District of Brownsville, and 46 in the 8th and 9th District neighborhoods south of the Bronx.
Noting the loss of five school aid on eight employees at Public School 36 in Harlem, where 68% of schoolchildren live in poverty, the prosecution claim that "this is not a neighborhood of wealthy parents who can bring funds to fill the budget gap."
The budget of 36 public school has been reduced from 3.26% this year. Funds have also been lost when the city has changed its calculation of the additional funding for each registration of disadvantaged students.
The union also claims that the directors of high schools have been misled by certain terms in a memo authorizing the dismissal of parent coordinators.
The memo employed the term "overshoot" to describe the action, even though "overshoot" describes the action usually move a school teacher to a group of available workers whose salaries are paid by the central office.
According to the draft complaints, "sixty-six parent coordinators have been laid off," and "not just for overtaking."
Mission: Congress is an agreement on the issue of Libya
It seems finally that the Republicans and Democrats have reached an agreement on Capitol Hill on the issue of the uprising in Libya.
It took a successful uprising, capture and death of the dictator long Muammar Qaddafi as well as the American involvement.
The Committee on Foreign Relations of the Senate will have to take a decision next Tuesday, supported by President John Kerry (Democrat - Massachusetts, with Senators John McCain (Republican - Arizona) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent - Connecticut), applauding the Libyan people for their revolt and American troops for their "courage."
"This resolution is to honour the courage of Libyans when they begin to rebuild their country," said John Kerry.
"It is a bipartisan support for their democratic aspirations."
The language may be harmless but the debate on Libya has never been easy so far.
This summer, legislators from both parties came into conflict, as well as with the White House, several resolutions to approve the military role of the United States in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain have submitted a resolution to authorize the limited use of American military forces in Libya.
The bill was defeated by a wide bipartisan margin and has never been subject to a vote in the Senate.
But on the same day the failure of the bill, the Chamber of Deputies also rejected a measure to reduce funding for US operations in Libya.
The US mission is therefore remained under a form of legislative purgatory - Congress sufficiently upset to criticize the management of the mission by Obama, but not enough to pull the rug out from under the feet.
The indecision of Congress has been overtaken by events.
Tripoli has fallen under the insurgents in August and Gaddafi was killed on 20 October last year.
The NATO mission was officially completed on October 31.
The Senate can now act.
The resolution of the Foreign Relations Committee "congratulate the Libyan people for his extraordinary courage and determination to freedom" and "congratulate the men and women of the US armed forces and their coalition partners engaged in military operations to protect the Libyan people for their courage and great professionalism."
The resolution also says "the national interest of the United States to achieve an irreversible and successful transition to democracy in Libya."
The new measure will win it the support of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Senate or divide it legislators like last June?
The senator and chairman of the Commission D. Richard Lugar (Independent) objected to the latest version.
His spokesman said on Monday that D. Richard Lugar had not yet read the latest version of the new project.
Within the Capitol, the House must vote this week an amendment to the Constitution to achieve a balanced budget, a legislative priority for nearly all congressional Republicans and some Democrats.
The measure, supported by the Republican Bob Goodlatte (Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on the budget, or any other issue, to get a floor vote in the House or the Senate.
Other legislators have not so far managed to get their amendments, but it is not without trying.
The amendment Goodlatte is part of the 68 constitutional amendments have been submitted to Congress on a wide range of subjects.
Some are recurring - the same bill proposed in both the House and the Senate - and others are slight variations of a precedent.
There are at least 15 versions in the House only the amendment for a balanced budget, and another handful "to control federal spending."
Some of these bills are identical, but their support - including the new Republicans who wish to gild their CV - the chance to boast of being the "author" of such a measure.
The law on the control of the budget (Budget Control Act approved last August called for the vote in the House and Senate on the amendment for a balanced budget.
In March, 58 senators voted in favour of a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
Beyond the budget, several members want to limit the number of mandates during which members of Congress can serve, while Jose E. Serrano (Democrat - New York wants to lift the limit of two terms for presidents.
Jesse L. Jackson Jr. (Democrat - Illinois) has proposed a host of amendments guaranteeing the right to a quality education and health care, among other topics.
An amendment prohibiting marriage between individuals of the same sex is perpetually proposed, like the amendment banning desecration of the flag.
Some lawmakers also want to allow the cancellation of federal laws if two-thirds of the states are opposed.
Also greedy were members to offer amendments, they are not as fast as in the past.
When the 111th Congress, lawmakers have proposed 77 amendments and introduced 66 during the 110th.
The pace slows from the early 1990s, when members tended to offer more than 150 amendments every two years, according to figures provided by the library of the Senate.
But these amendments were not much more successful than they have today.
The last amendment to have been added - the 27th - was ratified in 1992 but proposed to Congress in 1789.
