More pity that respect for the troops
The event: a gala on Wall Street to reap millions of dollars for homeless veterans of the New York City.
Kid Rock sang a ride on the helplessness, frustration and loss.
Hundreds of soldiers, sailors, airmen and Marines around him.
The crowd in costume-tie is standing on its feet for a standing ovation.
"The military men and women are seen as heroes," said David Saltzman, organizer of the fund-raising in the spring.
A high-ranking military officer present at the gala, which was also attended by Admiral Mike Mullen, chief of Staff of the United States, has seen the role of troops in a different way.
"They have been presented as a kind of orphan," wrote the top-ranking military officer in an e-mail.
I am sure that the organizers had good intentions.
I know.
But it is not in compliance. Just pity.
The absolutely contradictory impressions illustrate the difficult relations that have settled between the military and a passionate but often distant American public.
Praise lavished on the troops for their sacrifices.
But they have a certain price, say some military.
The public is increasingly as if he was sorry for men and women in uniform.
"We are not at all of the victims," said Brigadier General Sean B. MacFarland, who led the troops in Iraq and will soon be heading to Afghanistan.
"But it seems that the only way to support us to lock ourselves in the role of hapless minds."
It is a very sensitive issue for the military leaders, who do not wish to appear not grateful or disagree with the public they serve.
They also realize that the anger of revenantes troops of the Vietnam War has been much worse.
Thus, most of the conversations on the pity in confidence among the veterans.
After the return of his two sons of combat with the Marines, retired Colonel Mark Cancian has warned that the public would consider their service from two perspectives.
Some people would watch with respect because they have been confronted with insurgents and travelled to distant lands.
Others will ask if "a veteran angry and violent lurks beneath the surface," said Cancian, who fought in Iraq and returned to work in the government in Washington.
When he was looking for a job, he said, he felt that some people who were to move the talks asked subtly if he would be able to cope under the stress of a demanding job in Washington immediately after his return from battle.
"When you raise the subject of the service, you are faced with negative impressions," recalls Colonel Cancian when he speaks to his son.
The difficulties of military arise, in part, from the American indifference to the wars.
The victories are rarely praised by a country also unfamiliar with the army, which sees little direct benefits of the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan.
"As a nation, we no longer value heroism in the same way as the Second World War," said Lieutenant General David Barno pensioner, who led the troops in Afghanistan.
Instead, the congratulations of politicians and people focus largely on the depth of the suffering of a military.
The troops are recognized for the number of times endured services, the number of lost friends or the extent of injuries.
The army in the face of growing pressure to crack down on rapists
This week, a crucial hearing will decide whether 28 men and women will go to trial against the army for alleged inaction on rape.
If necessary, hundreds of complainants will prepare the next.
The soldier 1 Class Elizabeth Lyman was 25 years old and pregnant night 11 weeks where she says she was raped by a soldier.
It was in October 2008 and she returned to his barracks in Miramar Air Station, north of San Diego, after having had dinner with a friend, when she met a fellow carrying a pack of beers.
He asked him if he could join her in her room for a drink.
" C " was an alarm signal, " says Elizabeth Lyman.
But the Texane has set aside its concern.
I thought: no, it was 19 years old.
"It is Texas," she says.
"I had to follow my intuition."
A few minutes after entering the chamber Elizabeth Lyman, the man was caught from behind, thrown by land and raped, she claimed.
This week, on November 18, Elizabeth Lyman and 27 other soldiers, some still in service and others not, wait anxiously the court ruling in a landmark trial, which will take place in Arlington, Virginia, and who will decide whether a trial against the former Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and his predecessor, Donald Rumsfeld, will take place.
They are accused of not having stopped the spread of rape within the army, and undermining the constitutional rights of soldiers.
Classified in February by Susan Burke, a lawyer in Washington, the trial involved initially 17 plaintiffs, which amounted to 28 months - 25 women and 3 men, all claiming to have been raped or sexually abused by fellow soldiers; they also claim that the army was not investigated, prosecuted or provided appropriate justice after the alleged attacks.
Susan Burke says the military galonnées, because the problem starts with them.
"The army is a vertical structure," she says.
"Individuals in a position to eradicate the culture of retaliation? Leaders."
The lawyer also said that since February, she was contacted by almost 400 other survivors, most of which could be part of future legal proceedings.
His strategy: instead of bringing all plaintiffs in this case - putting all its eggs in one basket - it will start several trials, if necessary, to keep up the pressure.
The defence team for the Department of Defense, led by the American lawyer Neil MacBride, filed a motion to dismiss the case.
The court documents, obtained by Newsweek, detail the strategy of the defence, and essentially the fact that the army cannot be pursued by soldiers in service or not for injuries in the armed forces.
According to a 1950 decision of the Supreme Court, called the Feres Doctrine, the federal government is not responsible for injuries sustained by personnel on active service.
"The alleged evil is inherent in the military service of complainants" indicate the documents.
The Defense Department has refused to make any comment.
Things have changed since the 1950s.
While women have still not officially, the right to go into combat, this distinction is recorded on paper: the front lines of the recent wars are rarely only men.
In Iraq as in Afghanistan, women soldiers teams play an increasingly important role, especially to come into contact with local women.
The result: these two wars, 150 women soldiers have lost their lives - two-thirds in combat situations.
It is time for the army to modernise says Susan Burke.
She is not alone in that fight: three other trials are ongoing in addition.
Has the law school at Yale, the centre of legal services for veterans is preparing a case against the four main military academies for allegedly encouraging a misogynistic atmosphere.
On the other hand, the non-profit foundation Vietnam Veterans of America is preparing a lawsuit against the army, focusing on the diagnosis of "personality disorders" attributed to rape victims in order to give their leave - a relatively ordinary, according to activists such as Bhagwaru Anu Service Women's Action Network (women), a group for human rights.
His group filed a lawsuit in December at the Veterans Administration, accusing them of discriminatory practices in how to handle applications for benefits to the people who say they have been victims of sexual assault in the service.
Nine bills independent of each other have been submitted to Congress by a bipartisan mix of senators and representatives, proposing various solutions.
In 2010, $3.158 sexual assaults were recorded after the centre of intervention and prevention of sexual assault (Sexual Assault Prevention and Response Office of the Department of Defense.
But it is well known that the number of sexual assaults is underestimated, according to its own estimate of the Pentagon, this figure represents approximately 13.5% 19.000 incidents this year.
The report published in March is also studying the percentage of lawsuits: in 2010, 20% of cases recorded in the army have been the subject of a trial - half the percentage of the civilian judicial system.
The plaintiffs in the case of Susan Burke describe their aggression as the first of a series of injuries.
In the case of Lyman, it informs the Military Police rape less than an hour after the fact.
That night, she said, he was asked to tell his detailed 11 times rape at various police, doctors and commanders.
She has suffered a "rape kit" (literally a kit of rape), and the blood of his attacker - due to a cut on his arm - was found in his bed.
Six months later, in April 2009, Elizabeth Lyman is sitting before a judge, a trial in which we asked about his sexual relationship with her boyfriend earlier the day of its aggression.
Six people have testified as character witnesses for the perpetrator, who was eventually acquitted.
"I remember the day when the verdict was delivered," says Elizabeth Lyman.
"I thought I was going to start having contractions. I yelling at the court."
" I was placed in a psychiatric unit, and when I am leaving, I remember saying to my commander " was not his trial but mine. "
Elizabeth Lyman was forced to consult a military psychiatrist, who has come to diagnose a personality disorder, making it unfit for service.
In January 2010, she was returned under less than honorable terms, preventing him from receiving any advantage.
Is this the case Lyman and other complainants argue or not, it is a long story, " says John Turley, a law professor at the Faculty of Law of the University of Washington.
However, he noted, "in my opinion, they should be able to move forward."
Only this doctrine criticized since its introduction is between them and a verdict.
I have always criticised the Feres Doctrine.
The army is decades behind because it does not have the same benefits and deterrent posed by responsibility.
"The odds are heavily against them... but it is important that they are trying," he says.
These things change only when the good have the will to fight.
If the trial is not in their favour, Susan Burke, the plaintiffs ' lawyer, will bring together hundreds of other plaintiffs for other trials.
"We will continue to fight against the army on this issue so that there will be no reform," she says.
Where until we would, one or other of the two options.
The walls have eyes: researchers are studying you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just a guy doing his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who acknowledged having been taken a murderous madness in Norway in July, leaving 77 victims, was facing his first trial.
While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, to discuss with some of the millions of nationalists who support the extreme right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Connectez to Facebook.
"We realized that it is not so difficult that trace," says Jamie Bartlett, principal author of a recent report by the group of DEMOS reflection on the digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool of the site to find the people they seek with scientific precision - how marketers are doing for years.
" Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of extreme-right groups in Europe; it has targeted with announcements, but instead of linking them to a new group or product advertisements invited users to respond to an inquiry. Questions related to their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
When they come into contact with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues have been able to interview 10000 followers of 14 right-wing parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"It is a new way of doing research," says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are men, young and immigration.
But surprisingly, those who combine activism online and offline-are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screens. "
" L DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new essential tool in the hands of scientists.
The focus groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the issues that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to the "I love," publications on the walls and updated statutes.
With more than 800 million active users who add on average three content per day, "supernova data" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research the site's name appears in the title of almost 800 percent over the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people that you could not approach in the street.
"Before, when you are attempting to carry out investigations on the people of the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You go to the party, but you would never have allowed to enter," says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids any - you direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could provide a means to identify and address the health and social problems.
According to a recent study of D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, the young students who spoke on Facebook exploits of intoxicated had enormously more likely to be alcoholics that students discreet about this.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as advisers, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status would too often alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you do not diagnose," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the centre for health, behavior and development of children at the Research Institute for children located in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and in another case."
Facebook also constantly accesses information of its users.
" The site team that handles data has studied the statistics concerning the situation in love and on the day of the Saint Valentine, the turnout in the mid-term elections in 2010 and an index of national happiness (thanks to the only information available - the champions of the digital freedom have long argued that the site could make available its treasure trove of data to other people for research purposes.
But Facebook users know that the site was watching, they like or not - in exchange for power playing Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is authorized to access your information.
But what happens when users of Facebook are part of an investigation that they have not even heard of?
While researchers have clear instructions on how to collect the information other than through the Internet, it is anything else online.
"I do not believe that a large number of users have already thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the Knowledge Lab in London, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of its students.
"As far as they know, exchanges were seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study to be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth a profile or on the wall of a user.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two entirely different things," says Neil Selwyn.
That is why, despite his experience as a technological researcher Neil Selwyn think a notebook and a pen remain the best tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace the real world and the contact with people," he says.
"The social studies are expected to address the social aspect - and the social, it is not in front of a computer."
