"I was not comfortable, but I am personally a bit advanced after having seen and heard the suspect."
Dressed in a dark suit and blue tie, Breivik remained calm and professional throughout the trial; he has watched journalists and survivors in the eyes while entering and leaving the court.
Despite the bizarre idea that Breivik belongs to a broad movement of "resistance," the judge has determined that it was not crazy, and he also said that there was no evidence that he acted with accomplices.
The attacks of July 22, therefore seem to be the work of an extremist rather than an entire group of radicals, which can be réconfortera.
But that does not reduce the grief and confusion felt by the entire nation.
"I would have preferred that it resembles a monster, but this is not the case," said a relative of a victim.
"It would have been much easier."
7 lessons lost interview with Steve Jobs, the cinema this week
After the death of Steve Jobs on 5 October, some have compared to Henry Ford - distinguished by technical engineering and inventor of the modern computer.
But what fans of Apple may find more revealing in an interview of Steve Jobs regained recently and which will be broadcast this week in the first part of a film on the major markets, is how this creative spirit had understood the process and work flow of products.
It was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer, identified a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a breeder charts - a man who believed that many business leaders had a "disease their suggesting that a brilliant idea is 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a brilliant idea of an exceptional product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series ' Triumph of the Nerds. " This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits down for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and unusual conversation.
This time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had to leave Apple; he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he said that the main copies disappeared in transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs a complete video is found in the garage of the director.
This video, slightly rebound, is the basis for the film 68 minutes entitled Steve Jobs: the Lost Interview, which will be released in cinemas next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to detest the in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic expose philosophies technological and commercial strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
Four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts in order to give a precise answer.
It also discovers moments when perfectionism of Steve Jobs reappearing, where it seems eager to hear the questions Cringely, kicking elbow to accelerate and move on to issues or topics of greatest importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prescient on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs assesses what he considers good or bad in other companies and its own vision on the future of computing.
