It was as large as a suitcase, had a small tube. I fell in love.
The teenager that I was returned with HP and began to write programs for this machine.
On improvisation innovation:
Several times in the interview, Steve Jobs speaks to invent new products on a whim.
At the beginning of his career, when he moved to sell some printed circuit boards, a customer asked to assemble a complete computer.
Working at only 30 days credit, he had to address the assembly and delivery devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big disputes... I cried over by claiming that it would take five years to produce a mouse that would cost $300] I have had enough, I left and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could manufacture for $15 and was incredibly reliable.
The big companies that burn out:
Well before it is reliving Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders would be wrong and losing control of their market share.
"Admit that you work for IBM or Xerox, you better copier or better printer, and after?"
You have a monopoly of the market, so the company does not meet more successful.
Sales and marketing can evolve, so [it is these types of people] who eventually lead businesses and specialized staff product are set to decisions taken.
The genius in product that has led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product from a bad product - the manual work required.
That is what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could hold the entire computer industry.
It could be ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
They have snatched defeat to victory.
Innovation as artistic form:
"A huge part of manual work separates a brilliant idea of an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it is changing and growing."
You learn a lot about its intricacies.
There are trade-offs... Some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling it to each other.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste; it is trying to expose you to the best products that men have created, and try to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso said that good artists copy and that great artists steal.
We have always ashamed to steal good ideas.
That is partly what makes exceptional Macintosh. People who worked above were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who have simply proved the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another area.
