The Asian Development Bank has called on India and China to prepare to help the euro zone to emerge from the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a decline in the long term that would prevent the development of Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, director general of the BASD based in Manila, said that the two economic powers to the fastest growing regions in the world should "do everything in their power" to accelerate the recovery of the monetary zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He warned the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India, China) to look at the difficulties of Europe "indifferent eye" and noted that an Asian financial support alongside leaders and resources of Europe would "avoid a collapse in the long term" global economy.
"We are all together in this crisis."
"Therefore anyone can help Europe out of the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times in an interview during the Economic Forum World in Bombay.
"Asia can be protected to a certain extent, but it is not immune."
"So if China and India can help, that nothing prevents."
In recent months, the euro zone has been severely shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of borrowing Italian is dangerously skyrocketed and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The thriving sovereign debt crisis in Europe has spurred fears that the global economy falls into recession, and has raised the appeal of the major emerging economies to come together to help the euro zone to find a solution.
Mr Nag raised hopes that the IMF would provide any aid Asian, but he also said that the bilateral assistance - such as buying bonds of financial rescue fund of the United States, the European Financial Stability Fund - offered a greater power in negotiations Asian partners in Europe.
Anand Sharma, the Minister of Trade and Industry of India, said that "India will do everything it can" to help the euro zone since its own economy now suffers from a decline in exports and a drying up of arrivals of foreign capital.
"Nobody wants the eurozone remains unstable and agitated," he said.
"We have enormous challenges and we need to maintain a high level of growth."
"This is not a choice, it is an imperative, because where would we work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help European rich when they face their own significant economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the United States, said that it would be politically very difficult to accept aid to Europe Indian 1.2 billion, of which at least 800000 live on $2 a day or less.
"One day, they will discover that the Greeks retire at age 50 and they go on holiday in the sun and they will find it difficult to swallow," he noted.
Lee Howell, the chairman of the World Economic Forum, also questioned why India reserves should be used to keep many Greek officials paid poorly managed that generate losses, as in the rail sector.
Mr Nag said that the eurozone crisis could cause "significant impact" across Asia.
Forecasts BASD economic growth of 7.5% in Asia in 2011/2012 now face "risk of loss" because of the threat.
He pointed out that the vulnerable emerging markets needed to develop "contingency plans" to protect itself from an economic downturn and large capital flight.
Severe warnings from the Pentagon on the potential reductions in defense
The Secretary of Defense, Leon Panetta, has increased the pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that the imminent automatic budget cuts would undermine national security; it has triggered a chain reaction of financial corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, gatherings of civilians.
The Pentagon already digest $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now feared that an additional amount of $600 or more cuts is imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department," said Panetta, in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach a budget agreement resulting in the so-called sequestration, would lead to 23% reductions as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a significant reduction and applied indiscriminately, would make most of our ships and our construction projects unfeasible - you can't buy three-quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously undermine other efforts to modernize," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to separate us from a number of our civilian personnel, and because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we should almost certainly send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the objective."
"These changes by the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our preparation."
The cuts affect possibly fighting troops, continues Panetta.
"Although the financing in wartime accounts contingency operations abroad is not directly affected by the kidnapping, the war effort would be adversely affected by the severe disruption in the core budgets," warned Panetta.
"The contractor personnel would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and supervision of contract that support the war."
"The manager staff salaries would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to providers of war, and the legal and political support would be disrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of automatic cuts on the Ministry of Defence.
"The consequence of a kidnapping on the Defense Department would trigger a rapid decline in the United States as the undisputed global leader of military power."
"We are vehemently opposed to this drastic action," said the senators in a joint statement Monday afternoon at the publication of the letter to Panetta.
"It is not a consequence with which we can live, and this is certainly not the one that we should impose."
"The kidnapping is a threat to national security interests of the United States, and it should not have to happen."
The letter from Panetta and recent warnings of senators are increasing the pressure for a budget compromise or an appeal to exempt the Pentagon cuts, remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly virulent about possible cuts, even though he himself came to the highest position in the Pentagon with years of expertise in the budget to Congress and the White House and knowing that he was faced with difficult choices.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary has painted a bleak picture of what might happen - a military with a shell, but no core.
"It is a ship without sailors."
"It is a squad without bullets."
"It is a fighter, without enough trained pilots."
"It is a paper tiger, an army barracks, buildings and bombs that do not have enough trained soldiers able to accomplish the mission," said Panetta during his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It is a strength depressed, poorly prepared and unable to cope with potential adversaries."
"De facto, it invites aggression."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta stated specifically how further reductions could "generate significant operational risks: deadline for responding to crises, conflicts and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and risk assumed unacceptable in future combat operations."
And Panetta said that some of the biggest defence projects could spend at sunset, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
The list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a new bomber planned, the ballistic submarine new generation, the new littoral combat ship and the new ground vehicle, which would replace the Humvee army and navy.
Stop the development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is an essential step for improvement and response to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to identify a lie
A glance at recent headlines indicates how deception and lies are ubiquitous in everyday life.
The Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The administrators of Penn State have been accused of perjury for allegedly covered reports that a football coach retired sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone saying US President Barack Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsé countries.
The member of Congress from New York and celebrity Internet Anthony Weiner went for a fool by issuing quickly contradicted denials by irrefutable evidence.
The former presidential candidate John Edwards has been accused of violations of campaign financing related to coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who experienced history will never forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton has triggered by lying in his second term ​ on its ​ sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating on tests of school and university are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given the answers to tests students to do their performance evaluations.
Mentors should teach the contrary to send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of them are white lies.
Another study showed that foreigners are deceiving three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detect or detect lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game similar to, say, charades, where the objective is to say "I have had," the detection of deception is a serious industry knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities have conducted a thorough search of such projects, notably in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about the lies were démystifiés.
The liars look at you in the eye.
They bégayent, feeling or not always dangle.
Not conclude that the liars are difficult to detect and difficult to detect.
A lie called detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the declaration, micro-facial expressions, the formation of the issue and the response time.
I spent several years examining scientific results in the wide body and still emerging knowledge on deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern competence that is easy to learn and helpful to navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
The good liars are adept at reading the others, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that the outgoing lie more than the introvert, men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on the other" - usually to protect the feelings of someone - that married people less often lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge.
We also know that if you are seen as a mécréant, others will feel less guilty of lying.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
Firstly, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That is what is called "establish benchmarks."
This helps to provide a benchmark for measuring the subsequent changes.
Look at the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone is stirring normally his feet continuously in order not to launch unjust accusations when you see the stirring the feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and nonverbal deceptive behaviour.
Consider these indices as red flags, no evidence of deception.
The misleading people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their history, they can target their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, changing posture significantly or submit a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the difficult questions are the past.
The interrogators often falsely indicate that maintenance is completed just to try to trigger the reaction post-interview.
Also, beware of the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson misfired using the past while claiming that his wife murdered was alive, triggering a national search to find.
The misleading individuals can also use language outpaced: "I have not had sexual relations with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or entirely repeat a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "waffle" in its response to a difficult question: "well... to tell the truth... if I remember property... to my knowledge."
This makes the perceptual response rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize the deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid victimization by hustlers in their professional and personal lives.
