The company announced the decision at a press conference on Capitol Hill from Nebraska.
The official TransCanada, Alex Pourbax, says that the company remains confident that it will eventually get the approval of a pipeline, but with a different route.
This follows the announcement by the State Department last week that it would delay its decision to grant a federal permit for the project until it receives further studies of potential routes to avoid areas dunes of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast underground water sources.
"It is a real way forward," said Terry Lee, a Republican from Nebraska to Fox News.
The new environmental review commissioned by the State Department would probably have postponed any decision until 2013, after the elections next year, although officials deny the involvement of politics in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as a decision by the State Department, and expressed his support.
The pipeline of 2.735 km extends from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would carry 700000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would have to pass through six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, which have relied on the 20000 estimated jobs related to the pipeline.
But the Nebraska legislators opposed to the plan are pushing a bill to force the remoteness of the region's Sand Hills and the Ogallala aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
