The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government will face a crisis that brought the country to the brink of economic disaster
The prime minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the president of Italy to present the new government will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that it can form the government.
It is expected that it presents a new cabinet in its majorities by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his post.
Monti said he would present the results to the chairman of his conversations with the political parties in his essay to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in the ability of our country to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for journalists.
Monti has not explicitly said that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
"The framework is now well-worn path," he added.
Monti has completed the process to form a government in less than three days in a shorter time than normal, while Italy fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of its debt levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Mario Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to recover confidence in Italy who had been affected.
Highlighting the pressure on Monti to dispatch, market instability in the performance of BTP Italian 10-year bond above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland have duu be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers ' Confindustria, told the media after his meeting with Monti: "we said that we would support much this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to ensure this emergency situation.
The possibilities of Monti's success has been significantly boosted by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, in which the crisis has forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti will have a good result," said the press Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right.
The support of PDL party, the largest Italian, is significant because until now many of its members were opposed to the government technocrat majority that Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new government of Monti must have a strong parliamentary support to implement what will probably be reforms unpopular austerity.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began Monday its consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers ' groups and juveniles and women's organizations.
He will tour meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who has empowered an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the cost of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty about the success of the new prime minister.
Save Italy, with a public debt of EUR 1.9 trillion, it would be too much for the current financial defences of Eurozone.
Monti said that his Government should persist up to future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will give him only the time to implement the reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist that it must be formed only by specialists, an index of their objections before a process required by the financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that the mutual suspicions and disagreements between the parties complicate the trial to include political figures.
