Quinteto has included the country in turn to celebrate two decades trajectory
"Go to Costa Rica is a dream that became reality"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, the bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam, said that the group is ready to offer one of the best concerts next Sunday on the National Stadium.
They waited more than 20 years, but the group ensures that for them it will be a dream come true to occur in this country.
It is that the bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of his tour to celebrate two decades of work and Sunday 20 will be its sole stop in Central America.
That day will be on the National Stadium, from 19: 30.00 p.m., alongside the group Los Angeles The X and national Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt of the conversation, the full transcript is in La Nación on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans live?
Go to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us.
It is the second time in the South and Central America and so far it has been magnificent.
I have spent in Costa Rica only once the holidays; it is a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days.
We therefore émotionne to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the group, fans live with intensity the previous day.
What is your message for your most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying beside us for all these years.
There have been 21 years so that we can arrive at Costa Rica; thank you for having waited so long and we are sorry that so much time had to spend up to this concert.
Some people are already saying that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
What this adds a bit of pressure on your visit.
Some of the greatest shows that we have offered during the last 21 years took place in the last two weeks.
We have offered a two huge shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that this has put us in good shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are very eager to produce.
We love this country, we like to surf and the jungle; for two things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How have you discovered Costa Rica and waves for surfing?
We have a lot of friends surfers and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and waves are amazing.
My friends would always make surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, alongside Mexico, are great places to make surfing; that is what we learned through the gentes who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, offered with huge shows, with great songs.
What do you have planned for your presentation to Costa Rica?
As we have never produced there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best possible show, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What is this?
I think it is partly because we have nine discs and we can interpret more than 120 songs and everybody likes different songs, that is why it is very difficult to choose which songs interpret each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we no longer have interpreted for a very long time, it helps us to stay focused and surprise us because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved these songs and that we can have forgotten.
It is that the show is more interesting for us, and therefore I think it is also becoming more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
In retrospect, it is hard to believe everything that you have succeeded?
Yes, absolutely.
In the first place, I believe that none of us had imagined that we would form a large rock group, and the fact that we have done for more than 20 years that it seems a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and be able to continue to make music together, we émotionne much.
We love and we love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things could only get better for us.
That means for you to have been a key element in the creation of the grunge?
This has always been an honour for us to form part of this group of large groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group is a city, but it is much more bizarre when five or ten groups emerge at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to form part of the group in Seattle.
We are playing with some of them from time to time.
Last year we attended a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden in their tour, so we are fortunate to still be friends with all of them and it is an honour for us to form part of its Seattle has arises.
It is also very strange that a group like your continues united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much more time than many groups normally lasts.
In the first place, I think we are all lucky to be alive and, secondly, we are all concerned for others.
We are all close friends, and that there are musical boulevards that give freedom to each experiment.
We trust each other with the music of everyone and it could get better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure that we do not spend too much time on tour because it is easy to fall into the hands of big numbers and people who love music.
If we do not forget that people are there for the music, it helps us to remember that we must respect the music and what has made without realise that it is famous and a rock star, which is not really any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we have written good songs and at the beginning it was magnificent.
We were a group for almost three years and we have not published a disk before the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important is the fact that we are still very friendly with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), which began in the group with us and when I listen to a song or I see a photograph I think of the incredible person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to work, laugh, talk about music, football and many other things with him.
It is a surprising and we are lacking.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
It is true that you know his work, especially Eddie Vedder and for that you have chosen for the opening?
Yes, production has sent us videos with various proposals and that was the group that we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer direct and it must be very distracting.
Why you always change the words of Yello Ledbetter live?
It is a matter for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
It was he who sings and I think it is doing with the first words he imagines.
As bassist, what are its influences?
There are so many...
Among the first that I remember there was Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, that I could talk all afternoon on the bassistes that I love.
How has managed Pearl Jam has maintained the grunge in spite of the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the groups that I have mentioned, as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all those that arise at the same time, and if it is now, I think it is wonderful, because it is a music that is worth the trouble to listen and groups like Mudhoney are now the best music than ever.
At the beginning, his music had a more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What should this change?
It is interesting, because I believe that there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs like The End or Just Breathe qualified as very obscure songs, even if they can sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed has played for me, I cried when I have listened to them and they are deeply obscure songs.
I think that if you are growing and there is a trauma in your life and you lose a relative or friend, these things are beginning to influence your art and music and songs, probably represent it for me.
I also think that it can also be happy and even as it can be done to obscure music.
