Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A dactyloscopiste Cali rose to history as the man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these officials is crucial.
The November 4 dactyloscopiste ITC Cali spent in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farc, "Alfonso Cano" by confronting his fingerprints.
Seven dactyloscopistes working in the local offices of the ITC, this week it was the turn of " availability of Eliazar González, a man of Puerto Tejada, who has worked for 21 years in the judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, Gonzalez has worked in the municipes Chocó, where a lot of times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the corpses that had to be identified.
The year 2000, he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after classes adequate, he specialized in fingerprinting, which is the study of skin friction, that is to say the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano had warned Eliazar take with him clothes for at least three days.
Something very large.
Friday night he went to Cauca in Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and suspected that one of them was that of the man who led the guérrilla oldest in the world, therefore asked to carry the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the team of investigation to the corpse, it has not recognized by his physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed as a peasant in the area, without glasses and much more lean.
But fingerprints do not lie.
Accompanied by a galtonienne magnifying glass, ink, sampling and lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye was not wrong: it was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed the Defence Minister, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, it was the supreme commander of the Farc.
Research footprint
For a Sijín dactyloscopiste of Cali recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano," is very significant.
A lot of people not familiar with our work.
The fingerprinting is an exact science, no margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying the corpses, dactyloscopistes support investigations for crimes such as robbery and murder and confirm the identity of those captured.
When captured, many offenders are false identity cards or have no documents.
We take their fingerprints and seek in the database.
The researcher has narrated in a theft case he had to remove a section of wall of a house, because in this place the thief had supported his hand to get a safe full of jewellery and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not suitable areas for a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to obtain the footprint of the entire hand and identify the offender who had participated in different flights," he recalled.
Fingerprints can also remove or confirm suspects in cases of homicide.
Recently we found a man dead, with beverage bottles around him.
By interlude investigation has determined that a parent may be suspicious of crime and a footprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if no guarantees that it is not the killer, the scene of the crime.
A dactyloscopiste ITC explained that extract "the fingerprints of objects with reactive chemical or physical."
When they appear, using a sampling or a band for the levy.
Subsequently, the prints are sent to Asif, the database of déclinquents, or the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there is still a lot of undocumented Colombian," indicated the expert of the ITC.
He explained that not everything is how it is shown in the television programme CSI.
Like all that glitters is not gold, that affects is not necessarily an imprint.
However, it can be used, if it achieves the necessary confrontation.
The "indignant" defy the authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators jostled before the Zuccotti for camping.
A large proportion of people have joined the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The integrative movement Occupe Wall Street have defied the authorities on Tuesday in New York trying to enter through a judicial order, in place of Manhattan, where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another fleet of Great Apple.
Hundreds of demonstrators jostled before the Zuccotti, where they wanted to enter through a judicial order that allows ' outraged ' camping again in this place, while the other part of the movement has responded to the evacuation by occupying a park north of the city, where there have been new judgments.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to stand again in the place, we will move to another location, and we will continue the legal fight to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," said one of the spokesmen of the movement "is Wall Street," Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of ' outraged ' to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by the Mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came up to the courts, where Lucy Billings judge issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed the demonstrators to remain in the camp.
In addition, the ' indignant ' have occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they have managed to occupy the place, but after the Police has shifted and arrested some protesters, even though Bray was unable to confirm the concrete figure, ensuring Efe the fact that he has seen some journalists who were also spent handcuffs.
The organization ensures that there is Centenaries people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved as a sign of support for members of the movement and tried to intervene on behalf of the Police.
Meanwhile, the Zuccotti - which is a forum for private property - remains closed pending the celebration of a judicial hearing scheduled by this Tuesday, during which we must analyse the legality of the evacuation of this morning.
Some protesters moved previously focused and distributed at that time copies of this judicial order and they were the same officers guarding the place, which has caused some small clashes, " said Bray, who has denounced the fact that some official struck the demonstrators.
The judicial order prohibits the authorities to evacuate Occupe Wall Street or enforce laws ' published after the beginning of the occupation or prohibit the demonstrators access once again to the park with tents or other properties that they used previously.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, because of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and the demonstrators, which it has, however, warned that local laws do not allow to settle with tents and bags to sleep.
The councillor has personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn to Zuccotti, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and has been taken due to the fact that the demonstrators ' violated the law.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the place because it became "a place where people came to protest, but for violating laws and in some cases, to hurt other people," because "some stores had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life."
"The evacuation of this morning at dawn was repugnant and demonstrates that basically Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests of American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
Officials "occupies Wall Street" have also indicated that they do not think hold "major action" on Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions to commemorate two months of protestes, which started on September 17.
