Japan Returns after the earthquake
GDP increased 1.5% through domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral of the beginning of March
Since March the Japanese economy was paralysed, yet still recovering from the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe of the Japanese country since the Second World War.
The first estimates of the Government of Tokyo have calculated the material losses at $300000 million, which, despite the difficult global context, appears to be mitigated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page: GDP has raised a 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and a 6% annualized.
That the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - is the highest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is due, in part, by the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and the tsunami.
In fact, businesses have increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to 0.9% decline in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of rising non-interrupted.
However, the true stimulate the Japanese economy is based solely on the Keynesian stimulus which invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan woke up largely thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently represents 60% of GDP in Japan.
This variable has raised a 1%, driven by the increase in spending on cars, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of yen
Tokyo was handed over to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become a "haven" elected by investors fleeing from the debt crisis in eurozone and unrest forecasts United States, a privilege that hangs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a divided stronger products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, have been responsible for their poor results between July and September, the contribution of the yen.
While the markets continue their seats in the peripheral EU countries, the Government Yoshihiko Noda not drop our guard.
"We must follow the risks that remain, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the Secretary of State for Policy Economics, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Cooperation and Economic Development (OECD) said that the majority of the member countries have submitted in September more clear signals of economic slowdown.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points in the global economy has highlighted that the major powers have been curbed.
Because it fell four decimal places up to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Even eurozone was below average, which is located in the 100, n dropping eight decimal up to 99.13 points.
