The Queen stresses the "dominant" Spain regarding this type of finance
"Spain has reached a prominent place at the global level in the role of the Micro-Finance."
Queen Sofía recalled that the country has become in the past two decades the second donor of the planet with regard to this instrument of cooperation that the "essence" lies in the fact that it is "a tool for social progress, justice and hope for a better future for all of humanity, based on confidence in the human being."
The Queen opened yesterday the V-E World Summit of microcredit in Valladolid with certainty that " there is no doubt " that such operations are " absolutely essential " to achieve the Millennium Development Goals established by the United Nations for 2015, and " very specifically, for the purpose of reducing half the volume of people living with incomes below a dollar a day, which is the " poverty line ."
"Spain continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries in all corners of the globe, and assumes the task with "responsibility," said Queen Sofía, who had hoped that the initiatives and origins contributions during the summit, which will continue until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capabilities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women," the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have achieved a lot of objectives " and " we are facing many challenges. "
The summit of microcredit is considered not only as a forum for debate, but also as a platform from which we must initiate "two basic goals."
Thus, Her Majesty has explained that the aim is that by the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families who have acceded to these financial services and that 100 million of these families out of poverty in which they live now.
The momentum in the design of microcredit in Spain and in the rest of the world "has followed the trail started a few years ago a pioneer" by Muhammad Yunus, stressed the Queen Sofía as an "act of justice and recognition."
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of fighting poverty," which she is known since 15 years ago, when the Queen has travelled to Bangladesh to know on the ground its lending policy.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings like those celebrated in Côte d 'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "in every meeting I have seen a continuing evolution," said Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project gave him yesterday the adjective "head of the family" convened at Valladolid on the part of the "banking for the poor."
Finally, the Queen Sofía has finished his speech by encouraging people to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to advance in the fight against poverty.
"Ethical imperative"
The Minister of External Affairs, Trinidad Jiménez, warned that the "solidarity is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In this sense, she explained that it would be a mistake to vinculer cooperation with developing countries in times of economic prosperity, because it is a "permanent obligation."
Jiménez considered that microcredit involves "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty," and "now more than ever," the governments of developed countries must work under the criteria of solidarity and not allow that it is the victim of cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation."
