An average hides some differences: another survey, published in 2007 by the site management career Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40000 French employees surveyed reported having no sickness.
Another study, this time from health insurance, said that in 2010, 37% of the judgments were less than 8 days, 22 per cent from 8 to 14 days, 15% of 15 days a month, 15% of one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, the French workers are no more likely than elsewhere to work stoppages.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two researchers from the CNRS showed that between 1994 and 2001, the rate of overall absence (for health reasons or not) hovered in France between 10% and 11%, compared to 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the UK or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
