Legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, said a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
Palliative care, the committee is demanding that governments, health care institutions, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer.
The Canadian company lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk with their doctor the conditions in which they want to die and take measures to that effect.
It is one of the conclusions of a major report by the Royal Society of Canada, which was attended by six experts linked to a variety of areas, including ethics, law and medicine.
The committee recommends the government to amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, when this choice is needed, with a patient deemed competent to take such a decision.
From the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, who compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
If Canada was ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to broach the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77 percent of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, the experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die in hospital.
Overall, the country is in Quebec that this rate is the highest, with 86% of deaths at the hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report's authors arrive at conclusions that are contrary to the position of the federal government, which has already said it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also reviewed all the countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalisation leads to abuse, that is to say the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on not competent or not consenting persons.
On the contrary, said yesterday in a teleconference Jocelyn Downie, a co-signatory of the report, would be more cases of these outbursts precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians support euthanasia
Remember that 85 percent of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe that it would end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66 percent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of elderly or disabled has less value.
As for the people who practiced assisted suicide, surveyed feel 41% that they should not be prosecuted.
Peacekeeping or cessation of care to a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report.
Also in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it is stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a refusal legally valid is not criminal.
The expert committee also requested that health professionals are trained to the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
Palliative care, the committee is demanding that governments, health care institutions, and doctors are working together to ensure better palliative care, and that, beyond the cases of cancer.
Finally, palliative or terminal sedation, already widely used in the Canadian health institutions, the committee asks that it be considered when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it is subject to the same procedures.
Reserves other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the experts ' report of the Royal Society of Canada.
I am Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called "extreme" position experts signatories of the report, among other things, because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia for the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and have more than 18 years could ask what assistance to commit suicide," said Ms. Deschamps, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
Deschamps me also stresses that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
However, "in society, he says, there are beacons and constraints."
The specialist health law Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the conclusions of the report, which she called "clear pro-euthanasia."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, in particular the data in the report about the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, the Netherlands and Oregon.
The King of Jordan called President Assad to leave power
Damascus denounced a "conspiracy"
Syria is increasingly isolated
Supporters of Bashar al-Assad marched yesterday before the Department of Foreign Affairs.
Diplomatic pressure intensified yesterday on Syria's Bashar al-Assad, who, with the support of Russia, resists and denounced a "conspiracy" against the country.
Two days after the suspension of Syria by the Arab League, the European Union has stepped up its sanctions against Damascus, while Turkey and Jordan, Syria, have taken a stand in favour of a departure of President Assad.
King Abdullah II of Jordan was yesterday the first Arab leader to call President Bashar al-Assad to "leave the power" in Syria, where some 40 civilians and members of the regime's forces have been killed.
"If Bashar had committed to the interests of his country, he should resign, but it should also create the necessary conditions for a new phase of Syrian politics," said the King of Jordan, a neighbour of Syria, in an interview with the BBC.
For its part, the head of the Turkish diplomacy, Ahmet Davutoglu regretted that Turkish mediation efforts undertaken since the beginning of the year with the Syrian regime have failed.
"Those who are not in the Middle East peace with their people and cannot meet the will," he said, alluding to Syria, neighbouring countries to which Turkey adopts an increasingly hard line.
The United States are on their side welcomed a "strengthening of the consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime," after the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey to adopt an increasingly harsh tone" in the face of repression in Syria, noted Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime forces have died in the region of Deraa in southern Syria, announced the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH).
Two other civilians were killed "in crossfire and shelling with heavy machine guns to Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to the NGO.
At a press conference, the Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Moallem has estimated that the country was heading "towards the end of the crisis."
He has reacted strongly to the decision of the Arab League to suspend Damascus of its work, which he said was "a dangerous step."
Syria "will not falter," he added, assuring that "the plots hatched against Syria will fail."
After his decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now studying a "mechanism to protect civilians" and sending 500 members of Arab organizations for human rights, media and military observers in the country.
The French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also expressed support for sending observers to the United Nations to help protect civilians of the repression of the regime that he is "paranoia."
A new special meeting of the League is scheduled for tomorrow in Rabat to take stock of the implementation of the peace plan agreed on November 2, including the withdrawal of forces cities plagued by the challenge and the release of protesters arrested.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, ruled yesterday "incorrect" the decision of the Arab League, while China urged Syria to implement the plan out of the crisis, while refraining from supporting sanctions against Damascus.
