Monti takes time to markets and sacrifices Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has called for a little time for markets to form his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifices" to recover the lost credibility in the final months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in discussion with the political parties yesterday before today's meeting with trade unions and employers.
It should establish a firm relatively small composed of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important programme with a lot of sacrifices," said Francesco Mr Nucara, member of one of the many small parliamentary groups involved in the talks, after meeting with the Council president-designate.
The president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, for his part said expect Mario Monti sought by Friday a vote of confidence in Parliament to ensure that the new government has sufficient support.
The consultations will culminate in the presentation by Mr Monti a shortlist, probably a dozen ministers, the head of state, Giorgio Napolitano.
Mr Monti commented nervousness equity and bond markets yesterday, asking their time.
"Democracy, there are clear deadlines" to prepare a government and its programme, he stressed, saying "certain that the markets will be patient and understand."
His appointment by the president had initially been welcomed by the markets, but the concern has been especially after an unexpected drop in industrial production in the euro zone in September.
The designated prime minister should be a team consisting mainly of technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "political."
The new government must last until 2013, the date of the next legislative, he said.
According to the president of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new government will get the confidence of Parliament by Friday.
Mr Monti is committed, once in office, to work in the urgency and purpose that Italy "become protagonist" in Europe.
A spokesman for the European Commissioner Olli Rehn stressed that "even with a new government, our diagnosis on the Italian economy does not change."
The EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its goal of a balanced budget in 2013, despite the austerity plans adopted in recent months, including asking for new austerity measures.
The Italian "boss of bosses" Emma Marcegaglia, who will be on Tuesday, also stressed the need to revive the economy, "as a country that has no growth may not meet the parameters of deficit."
Mr Monti, known for its competence and independence as European Commissioner (1994-2004), represents a "change of time" for Italy after 17 years of "berlusconisme," the "professor" symbolizing the "challenge of seriousness" and "other" Italy, according to the newspaper columnists.
The great unknown is the longevity of his team.
President Napolitano would avoid early elections, because Italy must place by April 2012 to 200 billion euros of government bonds.
A Russian scientist helped the Iranian nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has helped Iran to develop a workable detonator with a nuclear weapon, said Monday an American NGO specialising in the nuclear risk.
The Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) is based on the recent report by the International Atomic Safety Agency (IAEA) and other documents from the UN agency to identify the researcher.
The IAEA last week expressed its "serious concerns" about "possible military dimension" of the Iranian nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, largely from IAEA document, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, had worked for three decades from the 1960s in a centre Soviet military nuclear Chelyabinsk (Urals), and have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 and 1991, he would have left the center to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
The economic problems of its society would have led to contact the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
It would then have cooperated in the Iranian program from 1996 to 2002, before his return to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA evokes "strong indications that the development by Iran of a" nuclear detonation system "has been helped by the work of a foreign expert, who not only familiar with this technique, but as a member state has informed the Agency has worked for most of his career on this technology within the military nuclear programme of its country of origin."
The crimes and anti-Muslim crimes have increased by 50%
Crimes against Muslims increased by nearly 50% from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, the other racial and religious violence has fallen slightly or little progress, according to statistics from the FBI made public Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence perpetrated against Muslims rose from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49%, against a 13% increase in violence against Catholics, a decrease of 4% of crimes against Jews and an overall increase of 14% of crimes and anti-religious.
The total number of "hate crimes" very slightly to 6628 cases, of which 47.3% motivated by differences of race and 20% by differences of religion, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and offences increase again," said the human rights organization Human Rights First, "the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant," the organization added in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights," said one of the leaders of the organization, Paul Legendre.
"The US government can and must do more to address these abuses," he says, believing that it could go through improved police reports on the "hate crimes."
The "hate crime" in the US federal law is a legacy of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation was adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, colour, religion, origin and now sex.
Twitter changes its platform and is more akin to Facebook
The site of micro-blogging Twitter introduced Monday, changes in the presentation of its platform to allow its users to observe the activity of those they follow, which makes her look like a little more service to Facebook.
A new "activity" and a "name" track more legibly, online activity "Twittos" other users which follows the messages ("tweets") and those who follow you.
This allows whether they follow messages if they subscribe to new accounts, if they have favourite messages, etc.
This new formula Twitter has been tested "on a small percentage of users in August" before being distributed to the entire network Monday, told the AFP spokesman Twitter, Carolyn Penner.
Twitter, which was known for his little instinctive operation, with somewhat esoteric terms (RT to rebroadcast a message from someone else, followfriday to recommend to follow another user) happiness insiders, opens to a wider audience with a comparable handling network public Facebook and Google +.
