Austria
Inclusion of a "golden rule" in the constitution
The government of Social Democrat/Christian Democrat coalition in power in Austria decided Tuesday to include in the constitution a "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by rating agencies of the sovereign rating of Austria (triple-A).
It is the Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann has even announced the decision at the end of a council of ministers, while the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the criterion of 60% maximum set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If the creditworthiness of Austria was lowered one notch, from AAA to AA +, we should pay EUR 3 billion in interest every year," argued Vice-Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is responding to a request from the Brussels summit of member countries of the euro zone of 26 October: heads of state and government had claimed the listing by the end of 2012, the reduction of public deficits and a return to balance public accounts in the constitution or a law of equal value.
The system adopted by the Austrian government is close to the " German model ," Germany was the first European country to adopt such a rule. "
By 2017, the structural public deficit will decrease each year by 0.75 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP) and, starting in 2017, the public structural deficit of the federal government should not exceed each year 0.35% of GDP, while the regional states and municipalities will have to submit balanced budgets.
The goal is to pass on the horizon 2020/21 public debt below the 60 percent criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
Strong yen
Noda threat of a new intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda, warned Tuesday that the Japanese authorities would intervene again on the foreign exchange market if the yen should continue to rise.
"We will do as we did last time if we see an excessive volatility" in the exchange rate of the yen, Mr Noda explained to the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen was not far from the historical levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on October 31.
That day, Tokyo has sold massively yen against the dollar in order to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just set a new record since 1945 against the greenback.
But the yen is regularly since recovered, boosted by purchases of investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar rose Tuesday under the 77 yen and the euro fell below the symbolic barrier of 105 yen, close to the levels that triggered the latest intervention.
Before the financial crisis of 2008-2009, the dollar stood at around 120 yen and the euro more than 160 yen.
The outbreak of the Japanese currency hurts exports of the archipelago because it increases the cost of goods made in Japan and reduces the value of income from abroad by Japanese firms when they convert the national currency.
" Japan struggle to rebuild since the earthquake and tsunami of March 11 that devastated the region of Tohoku northeast), Mr Noda stressed that the rise of the yen does not kill the fragile recovery in the bud.
The third world economic power has returned to growth in the third quarter -1.5% compared to the previous quarter, for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and household consumption sealed by the disaster.
But the Prime Minister has ruled that the yen's prices did not reflect "the economic fundamentals of Japan."
The Minister of Finance, Jun Azumi, for its part, has called on the Bank of Japan inject), which opened Tuesday a two-day meeting of its monetary policy council, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the deputy governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the inject had already taken "appropriate measures," suggesting that no further monetary easing was expected Wednesday.
At its last meeting in late October, the institute emissions increased by 5000 billion yen (47 billion euros) its purchases of Treasury bonds, to 55000 billion yen (519 billion euros) the maximum amounts that it devotes to purchases of various financial securities for flooding the market with liquidity.
Euro area:
Rates are rising, the flanchent
The risk of contagion from the debt crisis still undermines the European indices.
Despite the appointment of new heads of government in Greece and Italy and better growth figures in France and Germany, the rates of vulnerable countries continue their ascent.
Still worried about the stability of the euro zone, Europe's stock markets sink in a little more negative territory Tuesday, 15 November.
In Paris, at 10.00 a.m., the CAC 40 lost 1.4% 3064 points.
The Frankfurt Dax to give 0.4 percent and London 0.1%.
"With the new tensions on the bond yields of the states of the euro zone in difficulty, stock markets around the world continue to make part of their recent gains."
"Investors, nervous, are only too aware of the risk of contagion," said Terry Pratt, institutional dealer at IG Markets, quoted by Reuters.
The Tokyo Stock Exchange closed down 0.7%, in turn, renewed fears of market players about Europe's ability to contain the debt crisis.
"Japan, like the rest of the world has its eyes on Europe and exchanges will continue in a narrow corridor variations as investors do not have evidence that the situation is stabilized," said Mitsushige Akino, manager of funds among Ichiyoshi Investment Management.
This renewed concerns over the future of the euro zone penalises the single currency, which continues its decline Tuesday.
The euro is changing at its lowest level in a month and a half.
Around 10.00 a.m., the European currency is worth 1.3570 dollar decline of 0.4%.
According to brokers, it has fallen after the party of Chancellor Angela Merkel, the CDU, which met in Congress on Monday adopted a motion, including the possibility for a country struggling to emerge from the eurozone without leaving the European Union.
Italian and Spanish rates well beyond 6%
The borrowing rates of Italy and Spain remain very worrisome levels.
This Tuesday morning, the yield on Italian 10-year bond reached 6.85%, Spanish titles of maturity of 6.2%.
These tensions on interest rates in the southern countries, but also in France, continue to fuel the fears of stakeholders.
The head of the future government of Italy, Mario Monti has demanded time to markets to restore the situation in Italy, threatened with asphyxiation by the weight of its debt.
The new Greek Prime Minister Lucas Papademos has said that the implementation of the decisions taken at the summit of the euro zone on 27 October would be the "primary task" of his government.
Spain finds itself in the firing line of markets, whereas stand Sunday parliamentary elections in the country.
The rate gap ("spread") between 10-year bonds, Germany and Spain has reached a new historical high.
In anticipation of growth figures for the eurozone
Statistics aside, France has recorded economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, slightly better than the 0.3 per cent, driven by household consumption.
INSEE has, however, revised downwards the figure of the second quarter, with a decline of 0.1 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP) instead of stagnation.
And it truly is the fourth most concern economists.
Germany, meanwhile, grew by 0.5% over the same period.
A first estimate for the whole of the eurozone is expected at 11.00 a.m., while the European Commission has warned against the risk of a new recession.
Energy policy:
The facts must outweigh the dogmas
If there is one issue that we cannot treat from short-term considerations and emotion, it is the energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and business competitiveness.
It is healthy that an election date is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place is nuclear power.
The debate will only be successful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, sound data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic trends will lead to a doubling of demand of electricity by 2050, at least to deprive a huge part of the global population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will overcome the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce the electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases in the fight against climate change, a subject disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is the case of Belgium, which makes hers on the need to be able to find an alternative source of alternative or Switzerland, which will no longer just build that last generation plants.
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, for example, are continuing their projects with determination.
The United States have decided after Fukushima to add a unit at their park by resuming the construction of a suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island.
If the German model, focusing on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality irks the speech.
The choice of Berlin will translate into a rise in the price of electricity, energy dependence, exacerbated by the increasing reliance on imported gas, especially Russia, a leap of CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas-fired power plants and coal.
In a few months, all of these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to entertain.
European champions of wind, it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of wind; as a result, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity is 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an invoice of electricity of 40 per cent more than the French households.
While in a globalized economy, the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on national territory, French companies are benefiting from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Thus, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would create a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would make the illusory fine declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and defending the purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they are not opposed in principle to this energy, polls show.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has helped build an industrial sector of 125000 jobs directly and 410000 jobs.
Strong exports, it leads to a galaxy of specialized SMEs on international markets and makes the very job-creating non-transferable.
If France were to decide to phase out nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing alarmingly the EUR 6 billion annual French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would dictate an EPR designed to operate 60 years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of generating electricity miracle, it is diabolical.
The development by Areva solutions low-CO2, nuclear and renewable, testifies to the complementarity of power sources.
For nuclear energy, maintain the highest level of security is an absolute imperative.
In France we have a security controls intransigent and transparent on existing plants as the Flamanville site.
Our teams whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited the same obsession with security.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
One, Three Mile Island, intervened in normal operation; he remained without human and environmental consequences.
Chernobyl was the design of the reactor and unforgivable human errors caused the tragedy.
For Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw lessons from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
The result of this approach and cooperation between the security authorities, operators and French and German manufacturers, the PRT presents a design making it capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wanting to build a power station, the judgment of its construction at Flamanville is a magnificent gift to competitors of Areva and EDF leaves the way open to grab the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek out the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotion, dogmas and partisan tactics dominate debate as critical to the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration is a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from different angles - congestion police, judicial and administrative services subject to political figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed country status of human rights " of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students who made the news, the interior minister (read Liberation of 23 May) declaring that France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant servers."
But it is rarely discussed in economic terms.
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between left and right.
Right, the tone has been given by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that " 900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers, and to the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France " cannot accommodate all the misery of the world " in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden for the economy and society.
The only difference is the level of generosity that we be prepared to pay towards immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande is confined to banalities, indicating that the co-development will solve our immigration problem. "
This idea of immigration as a problem, perhaps pay electorally; but it is economically very costly.
As the economists recall Ian Goldin, Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book summarising the latest knowledge on immigration (People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among the experts on the positive impact of migration on economic growth, wages and employment in the countries that receive immigrants.
Restricting immigration anaemic growth and night employment.
Fears vis-à-vis the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they can substitute for domestic workers, especially the low-skilled, exerting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary substitutes for national employees, performing mostly trades in shortage areas of employment.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract the national employees, and the most qualified in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it hard to work in a country that is experiencing a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants are that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% of real wages in the long term.
And without taking into account the fact that diversity made by immigrants contributes to creating ideas and economic growth (high proportion of immigrants naturalized among the American Nobel Prize; Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants.
Migrants are also net contributors of social systems, an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that an immigrant in Germany, arriving at the age of 30 years will make a net contribution (less revenue expenditure) of EUR 150000 public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the mandate, fetching points missing growth "with teeth."
Teeth, serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy remains suggest European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember him for having invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, has experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but Franco in Spain, Portugal, Salazar colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be sufficient for democracy triomphât definitively its enemies, to exercise the vote, and the exercise of the most direct way.
You know, since Napoleon "Petit," it was an easy thought.
Universal suffrage for the necessary condition for democracy, there is not enough and may even be "instrument of oppression" as previously said the philosopher Etienne Republican Vacherot.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of power, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
Europe's crisis we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is equally and primarily a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodie of true-false Greek referendum will be held in this regard double litmus test: the need for a powerful return policy, but also the unsettling feeling of its inability to its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be exceeded.
The truth is that the front lines of combat democratic today are displaced, and that many of them, Republicans soldiers are no longer in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by requiring a succession of national referendums held in necessities and disorganised.
A blank cheque to European absolute monarch or a leap into the void of nationalist reaction: what choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want sunset but an exercise, common, right, serene and continuous, choice and democracy, this time at the European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - cannot be more where stop " list - because there is a crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe which pander to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe who slowly loses its sovereignty, and with each of its nations.
The urgency is to restore popular sovereignty piloting the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The exit from the crisis will involve decisions at the European level that can be taken without a full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
Having long fought this proposal socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
.
But the thinking without a stronger political and democratic integration, and seen as such by citizens, would be a new madness and a new deadlock.
We must assume a new stage of European integration.
For the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The Revolution in interests could suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a more integrated Europe economically.
This cannot be done by building a more democratic Europe on the political front, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
For Europe, are Europeans.
Smart cards "contactless" spreads
The World Showcase smart card opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in a climate of optimism.
The year 2011 should be completed on an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank card, telephone SIM card...), more than 6 billion units, according to the Eurosmart cabinet.
The fastest growing segment is the contactless technology that allows paying public transport or settle its purchases simply approaching the card reader.
This year, 460 million contactless smartcard should be sold worldwide, compared to 320 million a year earlier.
Their share is expected to grow in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent nearly 10% of the global market for smart card (6.925 million cards).
Long the laggard of the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground for the contactless payment.
Some 26 million Visa bank cards are already equipped with this functionality and 75000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400000 without contact Visa cards have been deployed.
But supermarkets put out all the stops.
Crossroads has issued this year by 2.5 million cards Pass contactless MasterCard.
To move up a gear, it is now that banks equip their clients.
"Two big French institutions have pledged to distribute future systematically to their customers ' bank cards equipped for the contact," says Gerard Nébouy, Director General Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Few devices are now equipped with technology NFC (Near Field Communication) needed to carry out transactions.
"They have fallen behind."
"But they should finally have a real boom next year."
"We rely on the sale of 80 to 120 million units in 2012 in the world," says Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
The Agricultural Credit yesterday announced the launch of a test to June next December at Caen.
The iPhone of some 200 clients and collaborators will be equipped with a holster authorizing the payment without contact.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the General Society also said yesterday preparing the marketing of an offer to allow its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
The Sahara in Nigeria, the terrorist front extends
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram.
Suspected longstanding ties between the terrorist group al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram is confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, has even said that Algiers has now "satisfied."
"The way in which the two organizations operate and reports of intelligence services show that there is cooperation," he said without explanation.
Paris seems to make a similar analysis.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger in January would be uncovered.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory should be killed the next day at the same time that several of their captors during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators to find several telephone chips belonging to terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of calls moving towards several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Niger man who has stayed at length in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram and the other a man who says he is close to Aqmi and the sect.
"It is a step forward, but we should probably expect more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it is possible."
"It has known for years that the sect has external financial support and intellectuals and that she is increasingly active," tempers Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, these "support" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or its modus operandi, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices increasingly complex and bill than those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of beaming little of interest.
A rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means Hausa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing a rapid success.
It is politicized and requires strict adherence to Sharia law while its militants engage the fight against the infidels, central government.
These are first churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, the militants of Boko Haram are particularly active, multiplying attacks on police stations.
The reaction of Abuja, as usual, unsubtle.
The army invests the city, there are 800 deaths.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, was killed in prison.
Therefore the sect will radicalise and leave his northern strongholds.
This Christmas, it claims an attack which 80 dead in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it is still in Abuja that Boko Haram blames HQ secure police during a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa which is operating from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria worries now all security specialists.
While Aqmi invested Mali and Niger, that Somalis al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat to the heart of the continent.
Last week, in an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready to share all information. "
