And, arguing that there is a need to rebuild America economically to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more fair.
Nord Stream, a new door ntrée Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, came into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with glamor.
More than 500 guests including four heads of state and government attended last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra and end buffet at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline which connects directly under the sea, Russia and Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, the French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart Netherlands Mark Rutte turned the wheel of the valve commander entry of Russian gas in the western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in western Europe by a first tube of 1224 km linking the St. Petersburg region in the Land of Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed by the end of 2012, for a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to the entire French consumption.
And it raises the possibility of constructing a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time for this huge site looks like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will allow us to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding overland passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine.
Suddenly, these two countries lose a bit of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut access to West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact," in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for Poland in 1939.
That is, if the topic is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supplies.
But it is the price of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between people of East and West.
In Russia, five years ago, upholding his vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries strongly gas consumers, whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us organically," François Fillon confirmed in inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how the major gas contracts are also political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom in number to Lubmin, to the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine is steel wrapped with concrete to protect against the anchors of ships.
It is based on the bottom of the sea, 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for the company Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to step up measures to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long snake of metal, heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, that nothing interrupts along its entire length: neither valve or station maintenance.
A platform check was off the coast of Sweden, but project officials have abandoned while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state company settle permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas in the pipeline is therefore released into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned to hear a leak every 100000 years.
Monitoring the condition of the pipeline is provided by a robot submarine, dragged by a ship for external observation, as well as a device that is circulating inside the pipeline.
The form of a cigar, it is brought inside the tube, broad one metre in diameter, and it is driven by gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 metres second book accurate information on the possible distortions of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate 50 years without any compensation.
The flow of gas is simply provided by the pressure.
It is 200 bars at the outset, and 100 upon arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to realize this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
Joined the German E.ON and BASF (15.5 per cent each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company for 20 years renewable, the entire building gas transmission.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas really transported," said Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was assured 30% by shareholders and 70 per cent of bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are safe to return to their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline is emerging from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted pine.
Valves, high of 4.5 metres, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and the characteristics of the gas that comes before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a book.
It was established 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It smacks of adventures, hours to write in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular coverage, elastic, leaves a white, as outdated by the time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook design but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, a consultant for the company, the launch of the new product.
The book is based on an ancient technique of production, the mole skin (skin mole) designates a cotton varnish used to cover benches.
This type of book was very popular writers and travellers.
"Moleskine has been revived an old and forgotten, who was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, now the head of the brand in Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces passed.
It is far from confidential production years, where only 3000 books were designed.
Moleskine exceeds the Italian borders and exports in 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a composite picture of the buyer, because the notebook seduced both the businessman that students and professionals.
The image of Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its infancy, almost 100 today and has since 2008 two offices, one in Milan and one in New York.
It distributes its books in bookstores, Fnac small shops downtown and was able to impose its identity.
"We have followed the air time and this new writing, despite the growth of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched a "detour" exhibition where architects and artists expose their own book.
In August, it has also launched a leopard coverage, on the occasion of the Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has managed to diversify its products: bags, agenda, pens, covers computer... The mark takes on a whole range of materials.
A success that has made envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why the unemployment rate for workers with disabilities remains so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive policy put in place in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still two times higher than the average: 19%, compared with 9 percent for the whole population.
Discouraging?
"No, said Eric Blanchet, director general of the Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people."
"The progress made since 15 years are considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times."
"There is still a great deal to do."
It must be said that for the disabled unemployed, obstacles remain before access to employment.
Rather, they are older: 37% are over 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the box and on the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10000 are disabled.
Finally, the long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38 per cent on average.
In short, criteria that makes the return to employment, and "are the crux of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses to recruit workers with disabilities.
So much for the brakes objectives.
The rest unsaid, attitudes are changing, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Undertake Precinct indicated that managers interviewed "a low level of awareness of disability," with an "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, emotional or intellectual disabilities."
Result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the goal of employment of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law... 1987.
The latest figures known, dating from 2008, a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, director general of the Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The evidence: the number of "taxed" institutions, like the amounts paid decreased between 2007 and 2011, 59000 to 46000 structures (and 606 to 480 million euros).
" The law of 2005, which increased contributions, has created a strong pressure on companies, " says Pierre Blanc. "
"But this also reflects a real awareness, particularly in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 percent of establishments from 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of businesses from 100 to 199 employees.
