Portugal very confident
Portugal's Paulo Bento begins with great optimism returning barrage against Bosnia (10.00 p.m.), this Tuesday in Lisbon.
The move, the two teams had been realistic.
"At the end of the 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, which is the throttles since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is actually only 90 minutes of happiness.
But there is a match to play, and an adversary, Bosnia, to destabilise.
In view of the game go (0-0) Friday in the hell of Zenica, it appears clear that the games are not facts.
Portugal has dominated the party for over an hour, but it was unable to mark this precious goal, which would have relieved.
"It is a good result, however, involves some risk because we have not marked purpose outside"
But at home in their luminous Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced to move, before an audience that should be there too, even if the party is obviously announcement "very tight," according to an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We expect a very tight game, but we are quite confident that they can take over," said the Portuguese coach for 42 years.
" We continue to have a 50% chance of being at Euro 2012, has downplayed the successor of Carlos Queiroz.
The zero reported Friday Bosnia obliges the Portuguese to score and win.
A zero may suffice for the Bosnians, who also needed to score.
"It is a good result, however, involves some risk because we have not marked purpose outside" regrets Bento.
"We are going to play against a team that has a lot of technical qualities and players with a lot of individual qualities," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese have the intention to develop entry maximum pressure on the Bosnians to do "not give them time to think."
A good idea, on the condition of realism, this time.
